51.9	Facial_Action_Coding_System	Facial Action Coding System	Facial Action Coding System is a system to taxonomize human facial expressions, originally developed by Paul Ekman, Wallace V. Friesen, and Richard J Davidson in 1978. Movements of individual facial muscles are encoded by FACS from slight different instant changes in facial appearance.It is a common standard to systematically categorize the physical expression of emotions, and it has proven useful to psychologists and to animators.	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/78/Illu_head_neck_muscle.jpg/300px-Illu_head_neck_muscle.jpg
